If you want to prevent any action or message when an exception occurs and do not want to handle it explicitly, you can simply have an empty `except` block like below:

```python
try:
    if file_path:
        df.to_excel(file_path)
except Exception as e:
    pass  # Empty block to do nothing
```

By using `pass` within the `except` block, you are effectively ignoring the exception and not performing any actions or printing any specific error message when an error occurs during the `df.to_excel()` operation. This allows the code to continue executing without any interruption if an exception occurs.
